In the United States, the political landscape often feels like it's dominated by two colossal entities - one representing the left and the other encapsulating the right. This division may seem daunting, but at its core, both sides are driven by intentions that aim to shape the nation's path. Conservatism, in its most positive light, acts as a guardian of the nation's cherished values and traditions. It's about safeguarding the principles that have guided generations, ensuring they remain untouched and preserved against the tide of rapid change. Those who lean towards conservatism focus on protection, emphasizing the need to hold onto the aspects of society that have stood the test of time successfully. On the flip side, progressivism thrives on the idea of improvement and evolution. It questions the status quo, asking critical questions about our current practices and seeking ways to address and rectify shortcomings. Progressivism is fueled by the desire to advance society, making it more equitable and just for all its members. It's a force for constructive change, pushing for reforms and innovations that promise a better future. The dynamic between conservatism and progressivism serves as a balancing act. Each ideology keeps the other in check, ensuring that the nation moves forward without losing sight of its foundational values. This balance is crucial in navigating the complexities of governance and societal progression. Understanding the intrinsic values and goals of both conservatism and progressivism can foster a more empathetic and productive political discourse. Recognizing that both camps are ultimately striving for what they believe is best for the country can be the first step towards bridging divides and working collectively towards common goals.  #politics #conservatism #progressivism #uspolitics #politicalbalance

Understanding this dynamic is crucial for navigating the complexities of contemporary political discourse. The emergence of this ancient psychology within the political realm is a pressing issue, potentially altering the very fabric of political engagement and decision-making. It begs the question of how we can foster an environment where the more refined forms of political thought can flourish, free from the intimidation and dominance of their primitive-minded versions.  #uspolitics #politicaldiscourse #progressivism #conservatism #politicaldynamics

The United States Capitol Building is located in Washington, D.C., at the eastern end of the National Mall on a plateau 88 feet above the level of the Potomac River, commanding a westward view across the U.S. Capitol Reflecting Pool to the Washington Monument 1.4 miles away and the Lincoln Memorial 2.2 miles away. At the U.S. Capitol the Senate and the House of Representatives come together to discuss, debate and deliberate national policy; develop consensus; and craft the country’s laws. As the nation has grown so has the U.S. Capitol: today it covers well over 1.5 million square feet, has over 600 rooms, and miles of corridors. It is crowned by a magnificent white dome that overlooks the city of Washington and has become a widely recognized icon of the American people and government. The U.S. Capitol’s design was selected by President George Washington in 1793 and construction began shortly thereafter. The U.S. Capitol is among the most architecturally impressive and symbolically important buildings in the world. It has housed the meeting chambers of the Senate and the House of Representatives for over two centuries. Begun in 1793, the U.S. Capitol has been built, burnt, rebuilt, extended and restored; today, it stands as a monument not only to its builders but also to the American people and their government. In addition to its active use by Congress, the U.S. Capitol is a museum of American art and history. Each year, it is visited by an estimated 3-5 million people from around the world. Today, the U.S. Capitol covers a ground area of 175,170 square feet, or about 4 acres, and has a floor area of approximately 16-1/2 acres. Its length, from north to south, is 751 feet 4 inches; its greatest width, including approaches, is 350 feet. Its height above the base line on the east front to the top of the Statue of Freedom is 288 feet. The building contains approximately 540 rooms and has 658 windows (108 in the dome alone) and approximately 850 doorways. The United States Capitol Building is located in Washington, D.C., at the eastern end of the National Mall on a plateau 88 feet above the level of the Potomac River, commanding a westward view across the U.S. Capitol Reflecting Pool to the Washington Monument 1.4 miles away and the Lincoln Memorial 2.2 miles away. At the U.S. Capitol the Senate and the House of Representatives come together to discuss, debate and deliberate national policy; develop consensus; and craft the country’s laws. As the nation has grown so has the U.S. Capitol: today it covers well over 1.5 million square feet, has over 600 rooms, and miles of corridors. It is crowned by a magnificent white dome that overlooks the city of Washington and has become a widely recognized icon of the American people and government. The U.S. Capitol’s design was selected by President George Washington in 1793 and construction began shortly thereafter. The U.S. Capitol is among the most architecturally impressive and symbolically important buildings in the world. It has housed the meeting chambers of the Senate and the House of Representatives for over two centuries. Begun in 1793, the U.S. Capitol has been built, burnt, rebuilt, extended and restored; today, it stands as a monument not only to its builders but also to the American people and their government. In addition to its active use by Congress, the U.S. Capitol is a museum of American art and history. Each year, it is visited by an estimated 3-5 million people from around the world. Today, the U.S. Capitol covers a ground area of 175,170 square feet, or about 4 acres, and has a floor area of approximately 16-1/2 acres. Its length, from north to south, is 751 feet 4 inches; its greatest width, including approaches, is 350 feet. Its height above the base line on the east front to the top of the Statue of Freedom is 288 feet. The building contains approximately 540 rooms and has 658 windows (108 in the dome alone) and approximately 850 doorways.
